'''Ahmed Al-Abbar''' ({{lang-ar|أحمد العبار}}) is a member of the [[Libya]]n [[National Transitional Council]] in charge of Economics.<ref name=list>{{cite web |title=National Transitional Council |url=http://ntclibya.com/InnerPage.aspx?SSID=7&ParentID=3&LangID=1 |publisher=[[National Transitional Council]] |accessdate=25 August 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61DEzFbAb?url=http://ntclibya.com/InnerPage.aspx?SSID=7&ParentID=3&LangID=1 |archivedate=2011-08-25 |location=[[Benghazi]] |year=2011 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> In this capacity, he is in charge of administering the Council's funds and opening [[Line of credit|lines of credit]] from other nations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Libya rebels in squeeze to manage ‘crisis economy’|url=http://www.tribuneonline.org/commentary/20110502com3.html|accessdate=29 August 2011|newspaper=[[The Daily Tribune]]|date=2 May 2011|agency=The Tribune Publishing Company, Inc.|location=[[Manila]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002192226/http://www.tribuneonline.org/commentary/20110502com3.html|dead-url=yes|archivedate=2 October 2011}}</ref> He resides in [[Benghazi]] and runs a company that imports [[agriculture|agricultural goods]], through which his family has business ties to some in the [[Senussi]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Levinson|first=Charles|title=Rebel Leadership Casts a Wide Net|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704629104576190720901643258|accessdate=29 August 2011|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|agency=[[Dow Jones & Company]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401173306/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704629104576190720901643258|archivedate=1 April 2015|location=[[New York City]]|dead-url=no|date=10 March 2011}}</ref>

