{{Infobox NRHP | name = Bingham Company Warehouse | nrhp_type = nrhp | nrhp_type2 = cp | partof = Cleveland Warehouse District | partof_refnum = 82003558<ref name=nris2>{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> | image = Bingham.jpg | alt = Image of a multistory brown brick square building | caption = | locmapin = United States Cleveland#Ohio#USA | nocat = yes <!-- to prevent locampain placing the page in the non-ecistent [[Category:Historic district contributing properties in United States Cleveland]] --> | map_alt = | map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|41|29|56|N|81|42|05|W|display=inline,title}} | location = 1278 W. 9th Street, [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], U.S. | built = {{Start date|1916}} | architect = [[Walker and Weeks]] | architecture = [[Chicago school (architecture)|Commercial]] | added = November 2, 1973 | designated_nrhp_type = November 2, 1973 | designated_nrhp_type2 = September 30, 1982 | refnum = 73001406<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> | website = {{URL|http://www.thebingham.com}} }}
The '''Bingham Company Warehouse''' is a historic [[warehouse]] located in [[Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], in the United States. It was designed by the noted local firm of [[Walker and Weeks]] for the [[W. Bingham Company]], and is one of the architectural firm's few utilitarian commercial buildings. For many years, W. Bingham Co. was the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest's]] largest hardware manufacturer and wholesaler. The W. Bingham Co. went out of business in 1961, and the warehouse was sold to a succession of owners of the years. The warehouse was sold to private investors in 2001, who converted it into apartments, known today as '''The Bingham'''.
==About the building== ===Construction=== Cleveland entrepreneurs William Bingham and Henry C. Blossom purchased the Clark & Murfey [[hardware store]] in 1841, and incorporated it as the W. Bingham Co. in 1888.<ref name=binghamco>{{cite web|title=W. Bingham Co.|website=The Encyclopedia of Cleveland History|date=2017|accessdate=May 11, 2017|url=https://case.edu/ech/articles/w/w-bingham-co/}}</ref>
In April 1913, the W. Bingham Co. announced it would construct a new building in the city's [[Warehouse District, Cleveland|Warehouse District]] as its new headquarters.<ref name=biggest>{{cite news|title=Wholesale Building Will Be Biggest Here|work=The Plain Dealer|date=April 22, 1913|page=11}}</ref> Intended to be the largest warehouse in Cleveland, <ref name=biggest /><ref name=newbingham /> the cost of the building and land were estimated at $1 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|1000000|1913|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars).<ref name=newbingham>{{cite news|title=The New Bingham Building Will Cost $1,000,000|work=Doorways|date=May 1913|page=7|accessdate=May 11, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dRxbAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22W.%20Bingham%20Company%22%20Warehouse&pg=PA30-IA25#v=onepage&q=%22W.%20Bingham%20Company%22%20Warehouse&f=false}}</ref> At the time of the announcement, the company had already completed the purchase of the land<ref name=biggest /> at a cost of about $400,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|400000|1913|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars), and its architect, the noted Cleveland firm of Walker & Weeks,<ref name=longlease>{{cite news|title=Takes Long Lease On Euclid-Av Land|work=The Plain Dealer|date=March 16, 1915|page=15}}</ref>{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}}{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=123}}{{sfn|Avery|1918|page=242}} had finished preliminary designs for the building. The architects drew heavily on Knox & Elliott's 1905 [[Rockefeller Building (Cleveland)|Rockefeller Building]]{{sfn|''Ohio Historic Places Dictionary''|2008|page=192}} as well as their own 1912 Renkert Building for inspiration,{{sfn|Johannesen|1998|pages=48, 50}} The warehouse, which was anticipated to be of steel and concrete construction, was designed to have a spur from the [[Cleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway]] (the "Big Four") run into its basement. The architects hoped to have as many as 17 truck [[loading dock]]s on the building's northwest side, with a truck parking garage in one of the three basements. Another basement would be used for the storage of the heaviest goods. Elevators were intended to be located in the center of the building, so they could be reached quickly and efficiently by all points on each floor.<ref name=biggest /> At some point in 1913 or 1914, Christian, Schwarzenberg & Gaede, a local [[structural engineering]] firm, was hired to assist with the plans.<ref name=lightmanu>{{cite news|title=Warehouse, Light Manufacturing|work=Steel and Iron|date=September 28, 1914|page=1197|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=76dAAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22W.%20Bingham%20Company%22%20manufacturing&pg=PA1197#v=onepage&q=%22W.%20Bingham%20Company%22%20manufacturing&f=false}}</ref>{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}}{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=123}}
By June 1914, work on the architectural plans had advanced to the point where W. Bingham Co. was ready to place an order for up to {{convert|2500|ST|MT}} of [[structural steel]] and [[rebar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cleveland|work=The Iron Age|date=June 4, 1914|page=1425|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sdYcAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Bingham%20Company%20Warehouse%22&pg=PA1425#v=onepage&q=%22Bingham%20Company%20Warehouse%22&f=false}}</ref> But city officials had extensive concerns about the architectural design, and extensive (if unreported) changes to the plans were under way in July 1914.<ref>{{cite news|title=June Contracts Dropped|work=Iron Trade Review|date=July 16, 1914|page=107|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n21AAQAAMAAJ&dq=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&pg=PA107#v=onepage&q=Bingham&f=false}}</ref> At the end of July, W. Bingham Co. awarded the contract for the [[general contractor]]'s job to the Cleveland construction firm Crowell-Lundoff-Little.<ref name=larger /><ref name=lightmanu /><ref name=longlease />{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}}{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=123}} Although the city was still withholding final approval for the architectural plans and building permit, enough of the design had won approval for the contractor to advise steel companies that it was interested in purchasing about {{convert|1600|ST|MT}} of shaped steel.<ref name=larger>{{cite news|title=Larger Shape Tonnage|work=Iron Trade Review|date=July 30, 1914|page=192|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n21AAQAAMAAJ&dq=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&pg=PA192#v=onepage&q=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&f=false}}</ref> Although the design controversy continued, the McClintic-Marshall Corp. received the contract for {{convert|1500|ST|MT}} of shaped steel in early August 1914,<ref>{{cite news|title=Tightened Money Market|work=Iron Trade Review|date=August 6, 1914|pages=234-235|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n21AAQAAMAAJ&dq=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&pg=PA222#v=onepage&q=Bingham&f=false}}</ref> the Ayer & Lord Tie Co. of [[Chicago]] won the contract for {{convert|9400|sqyd|m2}} of flooring<ref>{{cite news|title=Westinghouse|work=Iron Trade Review|date=August 20, 1914|page=325|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n21AAQAAMAAJ&dq=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&pg=PA325#v=onepage&q=Bingham&f=false}}</ref> and Carnegie Steel received the contract for {{convert|2100|ST|MT}} of rebar in reinforcing bars in late August.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bar Buyers Specifying|work=Iron Trade Review|date=August 27, 1914|page=366|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n21AAQAAMAAJ&dq=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&pg=PA365#v=onepage&q=Bingham&f=false}}</ref>
Final approval of the architectural plans must have been close by the beginning of August 1914, because excavation at the site began.<ref name=executed>{{cite news|title=Contracts Executed by the Fred R. Jones Company, Cleveland, Ohio, 1914|work=Steam Shovel and Dredge|date=March 1915|page=267|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0g5GAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Bingham%20Company%20Warehouse%22&pg=PA267#v=onepage&q=%22Bingham%20Company%20Warehouse%22&f=false}}</ref><ref name=excavincleve>{{cite news|title=Excavation for W. Bingham Company's Warehouse in Cleveland, Ohio|work=The Excavating Engineer|date=March 1915|pages=213-214|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eXMrAQAAMAAJ&lpg=PA213&ots=T2-o9hD327&dq=%22Bingham%20Company%20Warehouse%22&pg=PA213#v=onepage&q=%22Bingham%20Company%20Warehouse%22&f=false}}</ref> Plans now showed 10 above-ground floors (each of reinforced concrete) and three basement levels. At a total estimated cost of land and construction at $1 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|1000000|1915|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars), it was reportedly the largest warehouse in the United States.<ref name=lightmanu /> The Fred R. Jones Company did the excavation work.<ref name=excavincleve /> The work was extremely difficult. The excavation site was {{convert|150|by|434|ft|m}}, a large existing building abutted the southwest side of the site,<ref name=executed /><ref name=excavincleve /> and there was a very steep{{sfn|Johannesen|1998|page=48}} {{convert|25|ft|m|adj=on}} change in grade from the northeast to southwest.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} A [[steam shovel]] was used to remove the {{convert|70000|cuyd|m3}} of earth, and steel [[Retaining wall#Sheet piling|sheet pilings]] were rammed into the soil to prevent cave-ins along the sides.<ref name=executed /><ref name=excavincleve /> These pilings were left in place to support the combined [[Shallow foundation#Slab-on-Grade foundation|slab]] and [[Deep foundation#Pile foundation systems|pier]] foundation and freestanding [[retaining wall]].{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} Both the Big Four and the [[New York, Chicago and St. Louis Railroad]] (the "Nickel Plate") ran a joint spur onto the site,{{Efn|Getting [[Gondola (rail)|gondola]] cars onto the site was difficult. Trains had to move up and down a steep 7 percent grade, and make an extremely tight 28 degree curve.<ref name=executed /><ref name=excavincleve />}} then hauled the earth several miles to [[Kingsbury Run]] (where it was used as landfill). Excavation was complete in mid-October.<ref name=executed /><ref name=excavincleve />
The city issued a permit for construction of the foundation about the time the excavation was complete.<ref name=central /> The foundation used a combination of piers, slab,{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} footings,<ref name=central /> and retaining walls.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=121}} The total cost of the foundation was originally estimated to be about $50,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|50000|1914|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars).<ref name=central>{{cite news|title=Central States|work=Iron Trade Review|date=October 22, 1914|page=789|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n21AAQAAMAAJ&dq=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&pg=PA789#v=onepage&q=Bingham&f=false}}</ref> Soil tests revealed a hard bluish clay{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=120}} about {{convert|50|to|60|ft|m}} below the surface, and the piers rested on this clay.<ref name=central /> Cantilevered retaining walls with buttresses were built to hold back the surrounding earth, and two-way reinforced spread footings poured to support the walls.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|pages=120-121}}{{Efn|A spread footing has a base wider than the top of the footing, allowing pressure to be spread out over a wider area of the soil.{{sfn|Allen|2005|page=201}} A two-way reinforced spread footing has beams running perpendicular to one another beneath the footing to help prevent [[Deflection (engineering)|deflection]].{{sfn|McCormac|Brown|2016|pages=98, 485}}}} The William Edwards Co. building on the southwest side of the new warehouse left insufficient space for regular footings and a buttressed retaining wall to be used. Instead, {{convert|14|in|cm|adj=on}} [[Lackawanna Steel Company|Lackawanna]] sheet pilings were used to reinforce the wall, and two separate footings were built.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=121}} As construction of the foundation proceeded, numerous pockets of [[quicksand]] were found in the soil.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} Further investigation revealed that pockets of quicksand lay beneath almost all the footings on the building's northeast side. A test pit was dug, and [[Geotechnical engineering|soil engineers]] discovered a solid clay further down. Light sheet pilings were used to create [[Caisson (engineering)|caissons]]. These were excavated, and the footings carried down to the firm clay.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=120}}
The city issued a building permit in late February or early March 1915.<ref name=longlease /> Work on the basement floors and walls proceeded very slowly. Enormous coal and ash bins and long steel rails for the moving of heavy items were designed to hang from ceiling beams in these areas. This required the use of shaped steel pieces which had to be perfectly joined, and the pouring of concrete around them. Once the basements were complete, the rest of the building rose very swiftly. Upper floors were poured at a rate of three floors a day,{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=122}} and the exterior brick walls rose at the rate of one floor every two days.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=123}}
The W. Bingham Co. warehouse opened for business in February or March of 1916.<ref name=thebingham>{{cite news|title=The Bingham Co.|work=Hardware Dealers' Magazine|date=May 1916|page=1074|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://hdl.handle.net/2027/nyp.33433108133822?urlappend=%3Bseq=1088}}</ref>
==About the building== The W. Bingham Co. warehouse building cost $600,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|600000|1915|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars).<ref name=longlease /> It is largely constructed of brick, concrete, and steel.<ref name=naversen>{{cite news|last=Naversen|first=Andrea|title=7 Cleveland Landmarks Designated As Historic Places|work=-The Plain Dealer|date=November 15, 1973|page=37}}</ref> The slightly L-shaped{{sfn|Johannesen|1998|page=48}} building was {{convert|99|ft|m}} wide on W. 9th Street and {{convert|198.5|ft|m}} wide on W. 10th Street and had a total length of {{convert|435|ft|m}}<ref name=thebingham /> ({{convert|455|ft|m}} between the basement walls).{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} On W. 9th Street, eight floors were visible<ref name=thebingham /> and the building height was {{convert|101|ft|m}}.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} On W. 10th Street, 11 floors were visible<ref name=thebingham /> and the building height was {{convert|148|ft|m}}.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} Each floor had {{convert|57000|sqft|m2}} of space, for a total building interior space of {{convert|683892|sqft|m2}}.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}}
As viewed from W. 9th Street, the building had three basements. The rear (or southwest) wall of the third basement was actually a heavily reinforced slab and pier retaining wall {{convert|28|ft|m}} high, giving the third basement a ceiling {{convert|25|ft|m}} high.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} The third basement extended about {{convert|50|ft|m}} under W. 9th Street, while the second and first basements only extended about {{convert|20|ft|m}} under the street.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} There were originally only two large shipping doors, each roughly {{convert|37|ft|m}} wide and {{convert|21|ft|m}} high, in the rear wall of the third basement. To accommodate the doors, two exterior columns had to be omitted. In their place are two massive girders,{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=119}} each {{convert|41|ft|m}} long and resting on a single massive pier between the doors.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}} A railroad spur ran under the building's ell (along the line of the old Mandrake Avenue), and there were 24 truck loading docks on the structure's northwest side.<ref name=attention>{{cite news|title=Attention All Building Loft Tenants|work=-The Plain Dealer|date=October 8, 1971|page=47}}</ref>
The superstructure of the building featured unusually heavy columns and floor slabs designed to permit {{convert|500|psf}} on the floors of the first and second basement and the first and second floor, and {{convert|300|psf}} on floors three and higher. In order to accommodate the weight of the boiler, coal bin, ash bin, and associated equipment at the rear of the second basement, a portion of this floor was designed to withstand {{convert|700|psf}}.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=119}} The octagonal, steel core-and-concrete columns in this area were {{convert|59|ft|m}} tall, extending from the foundation up to the second floor.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} Four of the exterior wall columns as well as all interior columns in the three basements and first floor were also steel core-and-concrete, to support the stresses on the structure below-ground.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}}{{Efn|The cores of these columns consisted of {{convert|14|in|cm}}, {{convert|148|lb|kg|adj=on}} Bethlehem Steel H-girders. Their sides and flanges were reinforced with {{convert|16|in|cm|adj=on}} steel plates.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=117}}{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|pages=356-357}} The core, its flanges, and the plates were drilled to permit rebar to pass through, rather than around, them.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=119}}}} Above the second floor, all columns were reinforced concrete.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}}{{Efn|These columns were either round with octagonal or spiral reinforcements, or square with longitudinal reinforcements.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}}}} The bases of all the columns consisted of cast iron-and-two-way reinforced concrete.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} All column caps were reinforced with [[shelf angle]]s attached to the flanges and core reinforcement plates, and all columns were topped with octagonal plates reinforced with stiffeners.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=117}} Above the second floor, all column tops were flared to help support the floor slab above.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=356}} Due to complications created by the William Edwards building next to it, there were fewer exterior and interior columns in the structure's southwest corner. Instead, {{convert|7|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} [[cantilever]]s supported the exterior walls above the third floor.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=117}}{{Efn|The exterior walls here were {{convert|13|in|cm}} thick to help make up for the fewer columns.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=117}}}}
The floors of the basements and upper floors were poured in {{convert|20.5|sqft|m2}} slabs. These slabs were {{convert|11|in|cm}} thick in the basements and on the first floor, and {{convert|9.5|in|cm}} thick on all other floors.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}} The roof was a {{convert|7.5|in|cm|adj=mid|-thick}} slab.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=117}} [[Spandrel|Spandrel beams]] were not used in the flooring system. The exception was on the fourth floor: With offices to be located on the third floor, the architects wanted to do away with column caps in order to provide space for lighting fixtures and to avoid light-scattering. Spandrels in the fourth floor were needed to compensate for the weaker support.{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=117}} Flooring throughout the structure was Kreolite, a [[creosote]]-impregnated wood block.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Factory Floor That Stands Up Under Hard, Heavy Service|work=Factory, the Magazine of Management|date=July 1916|page=85|accessdate=May 12, 2017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q-U7AQAAMAAJ&dq=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&pg=PA85#v=onepage&q=Bingham%20warehouse%20cleveland&f=false}}</ref>
The exterior of the building was clad in [[Block paving|paving brick]] rejects.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}} Walker & Weeks had used uniformly-colored paving brick on the Renkert Building, which it had designed shortly before beginning work on the W. Bingham Co. warehouse. Architect Harry Weeks recommended paving brick for the Bingham building because it was strong, long-wearing, and inexpensive.{{sfn|Weeks|1916|page=5}} "Seconds" (bricks which were not uniform in color due to chemical differences, miscasting, or after spending too much time [[Curing (chemistry)|curing]] in the [[kiln]]) were recommended by Weeks because they created an aesthetically pleasing "tapestry effect which might be assumed to have resulted from careful artistic design, rather than accident and economy."{{sfn|Weeks|1916|pages=5-6}} Windows in the building all had steel [[Sash window|sashes]] and [[Safety glass#Wire mesh glass|wire mesh glass]].{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}} The roofline was a simple concave [[cavetto]] [[cornice]].{{sfn|Johannesen|1998|page=50}}
The interior of the building, as befit a warehouse, was relatively spartan. Five<ref name=attention /> elevators were grouped in the center of the structure,<ref name=biggest /> and a [[pneumatic tube]] network installed in the shafts as a space-saving measure. The building also featured several spiral package chutes,{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}} and an exterior surface parking lot.<ref name=attention />
The cost of the land and completed building was $1 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|1000000|1915|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars).{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=119}} All told, {{convert|300|ST|MT}} of cast iron, {{convert|1200|ST|MT}} of structural steel, {{convert|2300|ST|MT}} of rebar, and {{convert|38000|cuyd|m3}} of concrete were used in its construction.{{sfn|''The Engineering Record''|1915|page=357}}{{sfn|Buettell|1915|page=123}} When completed, it was reportedly the largest single-unit warehouse in the world.{{sfn|Avery|1918|page=242}}{{sfn|Historic Warehouse District Development Corporation|2002|page=25}}
===Architectural assessment=== The W. Bingham Co. warehouse building is widely considered one of the finest Commercial style buildings in Cleveland.<ref name=naversen /><ref>{{cite news|last=Kosher|first=John Leo|title=Bingham Co. Warehouse|work=-The Plain Dealer|date=April 7, 1977|page=D9}}</ref><ref name=peery>{{cite news|last=Peery|first=Richard M.|title=Victor Peters, 88 Was Bingham Inc. President|work=The Plain Dealer|date=July 9, 1997|page=B11}}</ref> It features extremely high-quality construction and design, which is unusual for a utilitarian building. It is also, according to the ''Ohio Historic Places Dictionary'', an early example of "vertical rectangular construction of a building in a manner clearly appropriate to its function."{{sfn|''Ohio Historic Places Dictionary''|2008|page=192}}
The structure is widely celebrated for the inspired use of paving brick seconds, which adds color and texture to the building.{{sfn|''Ohio Historic Places Dictionary''|2008|page=192}} The exterior is considered unusually sophisticated,{{sfn|Johannesen|1998|pages=48, 50}} with "subtle refinements of proportion and detail".{{sfn|''Ohio Historic Places Dictionary''|2008|page=192}} It has also won praise for the simple, repetitive piers that bring it to life.{{sfn|Johannesen|1998|page=50}}
==History of the building== With the completion of the warehouse, the W. Bingham Co. shifted from retail to wholesale-only operations.<ref name=binghamco /> Over the years, changes to the interior reduced the available space to just {{convert|500000|sqft|m2}}.<ref name=bryan>{{cite news|last=Bryan|first=John E.|title=Last of Bingham Inventory Bought|work=-The Plain Dealer|date=August 26, 1961|page=12}}</ref>
W. Bingham Co. ceased operations in June 1961.<ref name=peery /> Several executives with the company purchased the corporate indicia, inventory, and equipment and formed a new company, Bingham, Inc.<ref name=peery /> The new firm continued to sell Bingham products to manufacturing, mining, and railroad customers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bingham Industrial Line to Continue|work=-The Plain Dealer|date=May 26, 1961|page=44}}</ref> W. Bingham Co. continued to own the warehouse,<ref name=bryan /> and leased space in it to various kinds of firms (including Bingham Inc.)<ref>{{cite news|title=Geo. Worthington Co.|work=-The Plain Dealer|date=June 27, 1977|page=C9}}</ref>
Some time on or before 1971, the Bingham building was purchased by the Ostendorf-Morris Co., a local real estate investment company.<ref name=attention /><ref>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=Jane|title=Singing Is the High Note of Her Life|work=-The Plain Dealer|date=July 29, 1973|page=G10}}</ref>
In November 1973, the W. Bingham Co. warehouse was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=naversen />
Having been purchased by outside investors in 1970 and by Formweld Products Co. in 1973, Bingham Co. moved out of the building in 1980.<ref name=peery />
During the W. Bingham Co. warehouse's first half century, Cleveland and the [[Warehouse District, Cleveland|Warehouse District]] went into significant decline. The rapid and significant expansion in [[heavy industry]] in Cleveland ended about 1930, and contracted dramatically after 1950. As the century neared its close, only chemical, instrument and medical equipment, and plastics manufacturing remained as major employers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stapleton|first=Darwin H.|title=Industry|website=The Encyclopedia of Cleveland History|date=2017|accessdate=May 13, 2017|url=https://case.edu/ech/articles/i/industry/}}</ref> The city's population reached a high of 914,808 in 1950, but dropped to under 400,000 at the turn of the century (and continued to decline).<ref>{{cite news|last=Exner|first=Rich|title=Cleveland Population Loss Slows|work=The Plain Dealer|date=May 19, 2016|accessdate=May 13, 2017|url=http://www.cleveland.com/datacentral/index.ssf/2016/05/cleveland_population_slows_fin.html}}</ref> In the Warehouse District, 115 of the 175 buildings, representing more than half the area, were demolished.<ref name=litt>{{cite news|last=Litt|first=Steven|title=Planning a Smart, Solid Warehouse District Rejuvenation|work=The Plain Dealer|date=March 21, 1993|page=H3}}</ref> The number of residents living in the area had dropped from a high of 12,068 in 1950 to a low of 3,844 in 1970 (although they had recovered slightly to 4,651 in 1990).<ref>{{cite report|author=Cleveland City Planning Commission|title=2000 Cleveland Neighborhood Fact Sheets: Downtown|location=Cleveland, Ohio|date=May 30, 2003|page=1|accessdate=May 13, 2017|url=http://planning.city.cleveland.oh.us/census/factsheets/spa15.pdf|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211055131/http://planning.city.cleveland.oh.us/census/factsheets/spa15.pdf|archivedate=December 11, 2016|df=}}</ref>
===2000-2004 renovation and repurposing=== At the beginning of the 21st century, the W. Bingham Co. warehouse was relatively unused. A few small city and county agencies and offices had leased space on the structure's ground floor, while the remainder of the building was used for storage or was empty. Although the building had never been renovated in the past 85 years, it was in good condition. It was also the largest building in the Warehouse District which had yet to undergo demolition or redevelopment.{{sfn|Historic Warehouse District Development Corporation|2002|page=25}}
In February 2000, Bingham Burnside LLC, a company established by owners and executives of the Burnside Construction Co. of Chicago, initiated a process to purchase the Bingham building for an undisclosed sum.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lubinger|first=Bill|title=Window Could Close For Convention Center If City Doesn't Move|work=The Plain Dealer|date=February 27, 2000|page=H1}}</ref>
Bingham Burnside sought to redevelop the structure into a [[mixed-use development]]. The company planned spending $66.7 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|66700000|2001|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) on converting {{convert|379606|sqft|m2}} of space into 339 apartments, {{convert|292666|sqft|m2}} of space into a 340-vehicle parking garage,{{Efn|Architectural plans called for using the three basements and the rear of the first and second floor for parking. The front of the first floor would be retail, and the front of the second floor residential. Floors three through eight would be completely residential.{{sfn|Historic Warehouse District Development Corporation|2002|page=42}}}} and {{convert|21000|sqft|m2}} of space into ground-floor retail. Bingham Burnside hired Marous Brothers Construction as the general contractor overseeing the project, which it hoped to begin on April 1, 2001. To pay for the conversion, Bingham Burnside received a $2 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|2700000|2001|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) loan from the city of Cleveland, $7.4 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|7400000|2001|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) in historic preservation tax credits from the state; and a $7.8 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|7800000|2001|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) conservation easement from the state. The city also agreed to give the developers a 75 percent [[Tax holiday|tax abatement]] for the project's first five years, a 50 percent tax abatement for its next five years, and a 25 percent tax abatement in its 11th and 12th years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas|first=Corwin|title=Cleveland OKs Loan For Bingham Redo|work=The Plain Dealer|date=December 9, 2001|page=G4}}</ref>
Relocation of tenants was nearly complete by early June 2002, somewhat behind schedule. By then, the cost of converting the {{convert|693272|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building{{Efn|Footage reports varied. In 1993, ''[[The Plain Dealer]]'' newspaper had said the building only had {{convert|558000|sqft|m2}} of interior space.<ref name=litt />}} had risen to $70 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|70000000|2001|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars).<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas|first=Corwin|title=Bingham Building Job Hinges On 3 Remaining Tenants|work=The Plain Dealer|date=June 2, 2002|page=G4}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD) awarded Bingham Burnside a $41.8 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|41800000|2002|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) conversion loan.<ref name=corwinboost /> The Bingham became the largest HUD-financed project in Ohio to date.<ref name=corwinHUD>{{cite news|last=Thomas|first=Corwin|title=Bingham Building Will Be Largest Done By HUD In Ohio|work=The Plain Dealer|date=October 19, 2002|page=G4}}</ref> The loan allowed construction on the project to begin in the fall of 2002,<ref name=corwinboost>{{cite news|last=Thomas|first=Corwin|title=Bingham Building Project Gets Boost|work=The Plain Dealer|date=July 7, 2002|page=G4}}</ref> with construction expected to be completed in summer 2003.<ref name=corwinHUD />
Unanticipated construction delays meant that the Bingham apartments did not open until May 2004.<ref name=breck>{{cite news|last=Breckenridge|first=Tom|title=Downtown Lifestyle For Sale in Cleveland Warehouse District Inspiring Revolution|work=The Plain Dealer|date=August 29, 2004|page=A1}}</ref> The final cost of the conversion was $80 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|80000000|2003|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars).<ref name=breck /><ref>{{cite news|last=Zimmerman|first=Susan|title=Warehouse District Tour Supports Area Renovation|work=The Plain Dealer|date=December 17, 2003|page=E2}}</ref>
In late 2004, Constantino's Market opened in {{convert|9600|sqft|m2}} of space on the ground floor of the Burnham on W. 9th Street. The space, a former showroom for W. Bingham Co. hardware goods, was restored and conserved. Although the space was broken up by several columns, these were reutilized as display shelves. Constantino's received a $380,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|380000|2004|r=-5}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars) below-market loan from the city to help pay for the space's renovation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Breckenridge|first=Tom|title=New Grocery Store Is Marketing Tool For Downtown|work=The Plain Dealer|date=January 23, 2005|page=B1}}</ref>
===Conversion awards=== The conversion of the warehouse won two awards. The first was the Downtown Development Award, given by the Downtown Cleveland Partnership in March 2005 to Bingham Burnside .<ref>{{cite news|title=Carney, Rains Honored For Developing Downtown|work=The Plain Dealer|date=March 9, 2005|page=C3}}</ref> The second Award for Excellence in Renovation (Other Buildings), given by the Northern Ohio Chapter of the National Association of Industrial and Office Properties to Marous Brothers Construction in May 2005.<ref>{{cite news|last=Montgomery|first=Christopher|title=Developers, Architects Recognized By Group|work=The Plain Dealer|date=May 5, 2005|page=C3}}</ref>
===Ownership changes=== Burnside Construction suffered severe economic losses during the [[Great Recession]] of 2008-2010, and in May 2007 filed for [[Chapter 7, Title 11, United States Code|Chapter 7 bankruptcy]] (liquidation). Although The Bingham apartment building was 80 percent full and Constantino's was expanding its space on the ground floor, Bingham Burnside LLC was unable to make its loan payments without the support of its parent company. HUD seized the mortgage and [[title (property)|title]] to the building, and actioned off the mortgage.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jarboe|first=Michelle|title=Investor Files To Foreclose On Downtown Apartments|work=The Plain Dealer|date=April 17, 2010|page=C1}}</ref> Resource Real Estate bought the loan for $25 million in March 2010, and successfully completed a foreclosure proceeding against Bingham Burnside.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jarboe|first=Michelle|title=Investor acquires Quay 55's mortgage|work=The Plain Dealer|date=October 5, 2010|page=C1}}</ref> Resource Real Estate won court approval to sell The Bingham in July 2010 in order to satisfy the mortgage.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jarboe|first=Michelle|title=Bingham, In Foreclosure, Will Be Auctioned Off Soon|work=The Plain Dealer|date=August 14, 2010|page=C1}}</ref>
Resource Real Estate won the November 1, 2010, auction for The Bingham. The company said it planned no major changes at the complex, but would make cosmetic improvements to the common areas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jarboe|first=Michelle|title=Company's $25 Million Bid Gets Bingham Apartments|work=The Plain Dealer|date=November 2, 2010|page=C2}}</ref>
