{{infobox organization |name = Public Patent Foundation |image = PubPat Logo Blue.png |size = |abbreviation = |motto = "Represent the Public's Interests Against Undeserved Patents and Unsound Patent Policy" |formation = 2003 |type = [[Nonprofit organization]] |headquarters = [[Coral Gables, Florida|Coral Gables, FL]], [[United States]] |leader_title = Executive Director |leader_name = [[Daniel B. Ravicher]] |key_people = {{hlist|Margo A. Bagley | Michael Herz | [[Eben Moglen]]}} |website = [http://www.pubpat.org/ www.pubpat.org] }}
'''Public Patent Foundation''', or '''PUBPAT''', is a [[non-profit organization]] that seeks to limit perceived abuse of the [[United States patent law|United States patent system]]. It was founded in 2003 by [[Dan Ravicher]]. {{As of|2004}}, there was growing concern by many technology professionals over the number of [[patent]]s granted that are either too trivial to deserve protection, or duplicate existing or expired patents. It usually works by petitioning the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] to review patents that are suspected of being invalid somehow or another, usually by [[prior art]].
== Actions == * [http://www.pubpat.org/Congressional_Testimony_June2005.htm U.S. Congress Invites PUBPAT Executive to Testify About Patent Reform]
==Significant cases== * [http://pubpat.org/pfizerlipitor.htm Pfizer Lipitor Patent] (see [[Atorvastatin#Patent challenge|Atorvastatin]]) * [http://pubpat.org/microsoftfat.htm Microsoft FAT patent] (see [[File Allocation Table#FAT licensing|File Allocation Table]]) * [http://pubpat.org/columbiacotransformation.htm Columbia Cotransformation Patent] (see [[Richard Axel]]) * [http://pubpat.org/13 Forgent Networks JPEG Related Patent] (see [[Forgent Networks]]) * [http://www.pubpat.org/brca.htm Breast Cancer Gene Patents] (see [[BRCA1]])
